<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>9. Material 49<br>
As mentioned above this material is prepared from<br>
the neutron capture reaction in 28. So far only microgram quantities have been produced <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>so bulk physical properties of this element are not known</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
I think that the terms you are trying to use is not &quot;phase&quot;,<br>
but &quot;grade&quot;. There are three defined categories:<br>
<br>
From:<br>
Plutonium Isotopics - Non-Proliferation And Safeguards Issues<br>
Australian Safeguards Office, Canberra ACT, Australia<br>
IAEA-SM-351/64<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>3. DEFINITIONS OF PLUTONIUM GRADES<br>
...<br>
&quot;Weapons-grade&quot; plutonium (WGPu) contains no more than 7% of the isotope Pu-240. <br>
... Within weapons-grade there is the sub-category of &quot;super-grade&quot; plutonium (SGPu), containing no more than 3% Pu-240.<br>
....<br>
<br>
&quot;Fuel-grade&quot; plutonium (FGPu) contains more than 7%, but less than 19%, of the isotope Pu-240.<br>
...<br>
<br>
&quot;Reactor-grade&quot; plutonium (RGPu) is produced in power reactors and contains 19% or more of the isotope Pu-240.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
(It is important to note that all three grades are &quot;weapons-usable&quot; and can make reliable, full-performance nuclear weapons. It is simply preferable to use higher grade material, but it is in no way necessary.)<br>
