1. It is generally known that 50 kg of 100 % Heu is the critical mass for uranium 235.<br>
2. The mean neutron free path is 16 cm for U-235 solid balls.<br>
3. To get exact measurements of the  of the U-235  pit use<br>
the volume formula for its shape .<br>
4. The normal density of U-235 metal is 18.9 grams per cubic centimeter .<br>
5. If we treat the pit as a cube lets calculate the dimensions of it.<br>
6. 50 kg is 50,000 grams.<br>
50,000 devided by 19 grams per cubic centimeter is<br>
2631.789 cubic centimeters of volume .<br>
7. Applying the cubic volume formula V= S*S*S<br>
the sides of the cube all measure 13.806 centimeters<br>
8. Applying the formula D-2R then<br>
the radius is 6.9 cm.<br>
9. deviding 6.9/16 we find probability of fission<br>
to be 43% for each free neutrons fate<br>
10. .43 * 2.5 = 1.078<br>
11. .43 * 3 = 1.29 <br>
12. We know that U 235 + 0N1 = Fission fragments + 180 mev<br>
+ 2.5-3 free neutrons produce per each individual fission event.<br>
13. We know that each neutron has a 43 % probability of causing another fission and releasing 2.5 - 3 more<br>
free  neutrons one of which will surely cuase another fission to occurr.<br>
.14. This defines a critical mass, where the fission chain reaction will continue indefinitly with ouy dying out.<br>
15. When any neutron reflecter is used around the U  235<br>
ball this will increase the probability of each neutron causing a fission event to increase enough to create a supercrital configuration in the  U-235 ball. When enough  weapons grade material is used the result is an atomic explosion . <br>
16. This is the  secret of the Atom bombs physics.<br>
<br>
